---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Cosmic-web gas accretion";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Cosmic-web gas accretion</h1>

    <p>
      Gas accretion from the cosmic web describes the inflow of intergalactic medium (IGM) gas along filamentary large-scale structures into galaxy halos, providing fresh fuel for star formation. This process is expected to be important at high redshift (z ~ 2–4) and in low-mass halos where gas can remain cold and avoid shock-heating.<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>
    </p>

    <h2>Observational signatures</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Extended Lyα emission tracing filamentary structure and clumpy neutral gas (e.g., Mukherjee et al. 2026 reports a system embedded in a ~4 cMpc filament).<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup></li>
      <li>Low metallicity, high sSFR, and co-spatial Lyα inflow signatures in ultra-low-mass components are consistent with filamentary accretion delivering metal-poor fuel (Mukherjee et al. 2026). The MXDF example shows companion components with log(M*/M☉) ≈ 6.3–6.9 and sSFR ≳ 10⁻⁸ yr⁻¹.<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup></li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      In the MXDF case quantified by Mukherjee et al. (2026), the Lyα-emitting structure sits within a ≈4 comoving Mpc filamentary overdensity. The observed Lyα morphology is clumpy and offset from the primary stellar continuum by ≈0.66 arcsec, and the associated compact components have ultra-low stellar masses (log M* ≈ 6.34–6.91), very young mass-weighted ages (≲7 Myr), and high sSFRs (≳10⁻⁸ yr⁻¹), all consistent with cold-mode accretion fuelling localized starbursts. These quantitative markers provide a concrete observational anchor for cosmic-web accretion in low-mass, high-z systems.<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>
    </p>

    <h2>Open questions</h2>
    <p>
      How to robustly separate pristine cosmic-web accretion from recycled gas and mergers observationally remains an open challenge. Mukherjee et al. (2026) discuss that spatial coincidence and low metallicity provide supporting but not definitive evidence for cosmic-web accretion (Sect. 4.4–4.5).<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>
    </p>

    <div class="references">
      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li id="ref1">Mukherjee, T., Li, Z., Zafar, T., et al. 2026, arXiv:2603.11411.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
